<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION DIVISION II TENNIS; SUNNY HILLS DOMINATES RIVERSIDE POLY IN 
SEMIFINAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MELANIE NEFF, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "You remember Sunny Hills?" No. 1 doubles player Kris Mueller of Riverside 
Poly asked an alumni during Thursday's Southern Section Division II boys' 
tennis semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
 "They're still as good as ever," Mueller said as he watched his team lose 17 
2/3-3 2/3 to the division's top-seeded team. 
</P>
<P>
 The defending champion Lancers dominated from the start, leading, 6-1, at the 
end of the first round. By the end of the second Sunny Hills led, 11 2/3-2 1/3. 
</P>
<P>
 Two come-from-behind victories by Sunny Hills (21-1) in first-round doubles 
stunned Riverside Poly (21-3). 
</P>
<P>
 The Lancers' Joseph Gilbert and Joey Springer, playing at No. 2, took Brett 
Masi and Scott Merryman to a 6-6 tie. Down 1-6 in the tie-breaker, Gilbert and 
Springer scored seven consecutive points to take the set, 7-6 (8-6). 
</P>
<P>
 David Farkas and Jeff Hartl came back from a 4-5 deficit, breaking serve at 
5-5 and defeating Mark Vanta and Paul Vargas, 7-5. 
</P>
<P>
 "The first round took a lot out of them," Sunny Hills Coach Steve White said. 
"It took the pressure off us and put it all on them." 
</P>
<P>
 The Lancers again lost only one set in round two, when Farkas and Hartl fell 
to Mueller and Jack Williams, 6-4. Gilbert and Springer went on to sweep their 
sets, 6-2, 7-6, 6-1, and No. 1 doubles team Kevin Kim and Hiren Bhavsar had no 
problems, losing only two games, 6-0, 6-1, 6-1. 
</P>
<P>
 "You have to win doubles, you always have had to," White said. "Before we 
could develop our doubles, now we have to put our best players in so we can 
win." 
</P>
<P>
 White has moved Kim, his top singles player and No. 1 in the nation in the 
16-year-old division, to doubles and Gilbert, who won the Ojai Tournament 16s 
title also is playing doubles. 
</P>
<P>
 The Lancers now face Palm Desert, which defeated Redlands, 11-10. The final is 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't care who we play. Redlands, Palm Desert and Poly are all about the 
same," White said. "Actually, I think Poly is more consistent in keeping the 
ball in play than the other two." 
</P>
</TEXT>
