<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; NATIONWIDE; BLACKS WORRIED FOR CHILDREN, POLL FINDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Black adults are overwhelmingly pessimistic about the prospects of black 
children, citing fears of violence, guns, drugs and gangs, a poll says.The 
poll, commissioned by the Children's Defense Fund and a new organization known 
as the Black Community Crusade for Children, found that more than three-fourths 
of respondents said they fear that their children or children they know will 
fall victim to violence. More than 70% of the respondents, many of them raised 
in an era of segregation, said they believe that it is harder for children 
today than it was for them. More than three-fourths of black children polled 
said school violence is a serious problem for them; 70% said the same of guns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
