<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAX BARS MAY GO SMOKE-FREE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHERYL STOLBERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Although officials at San Francisco International Airport have declined to ban 
smoking in bars, their counterparts in Los Angeles are on the verge of doing 
just that -- a move that would make the bars at Los Angeles International 
Airport the first in the city to go smoke-free. 
</P>
<P>
 The Los Angeles Airport Commission voted unanimously May 3 to ask the City 
Council to eliminate smoking in all indoor areas of LAX, except one lounge for 
international travelers.The council is expected to adopt the proposed 
ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
 The problem, LAX officials say, is the same as in San Francisco: An ordinance 
restricting smoking, adopted last year, has jammed the airport bars and lounges 
with smokers, who now have nowhere else to go. 
</P>
<P>
 Airport spokeswoman Cora Fossett said: "It was causing a safety hazard, the 
crowding. Not to mention it was keeping nonsmokers who just wanted to get a 
drink from getting there." SHERYL STOLBERG 
</P>
</TEXT>
