<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF ROUNDUP; THUNDERSTORMS PUT COLONIAL ON HOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 No one in the field of 110 players finished a round and 57 hadn't even started 
when a series of thunderstorms forced an overnight suspension of the first 
round of the Southwestern Bell Colonial at Fort Worth, Tex. 
</P>
<P>
 The suspension marked the second time in three weeks that violent spring 
weather had disrupted a PGA Tour event in North Texas. 
</P>
<P>
 The GTE Byron Nelson Classic, some 30 miles away, was reduced to a 36-hole 
format two weeks ago at Irving. 
</P>
<P>
 Players marked their positions when play was abandoned at 4:10 p.m. (CDT) on 
the rain-soaked Colonial Country Club course and were scheduled to return this 
morning to complete the first round. 
</P>
<P>
 The 57 golfers who didn't start Thursday will play 36 holes, weather 
permitting today. 
</P>
<P>
 Of those on the course, John Cook held the lead. He was at five-under-par with 
five holes to play. 
</P>
<P>
 "With the forecast, we were kind of prepared for it," he said. "We were 
running, trying to get in as many holes as we could before it was stopped." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, he said, "it's frustrating to have a good round going and not be able 
to finish." 
</P>
<P>
 Tom Lehman, who scored a record-setting victory last week in the Memorial 
tournament in Dublin, Ohio, was four-under with three holes to go. 
</P>
<P>
 Nick Price, Hale Irwin, David Frost, Bruce Lietzke and Ken Green were at 
three-under. Frost had seven holes to play, Lietzke six, Price and Irwin five 
and Green four. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Nancy Ramsbottom, who has not won on the LPGA tour in nearly a decade, eagled 
the eighth hole en route to an eight-under-par 64 and a one-stroke lead after 
the opening round of the Corning Classic at Corning, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
 Ramsbottom took advantage of an early tee time. A thunderstorm forced 
suspension of play for nearly an hour, but it softened up the Corning Country 
Club course for those who teed off before noon. 
</P>
<P>
 In the afternoon, winds started to swirl and the rain returned, causing the 
scores of most of the late starters to climb. 
</P>
<P>
 Pat Bradley and Amy Benz shared second at 65, and Beth Daniel was next at 67. 
Martha Nause, Alicia Dibos and Karen Noble were among a large group at 68. 
</P>
<P>
 Ramsbottom's score was the best ever in an opening round of the Corning 
Classic, breaking the 65s shot by Kathy Young in 1987 and Colleen Walker in 
1992. She had a six-under 30 on the front nine, which she played as her back 
nine. 
</P>
<P>
 Laura Davies was at 70. 
</P>
