<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATURE'S DOOR OPENS; STARTING JUNE 4, PUBLIC MAY TOUR 6,600 ACRES OF 
LONG-CLOSED LAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID HALDANE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 4-year-old promise was finally fulfilled by Thursday's announcement by 
Irvine Co. officials that a vast swath of land that has been closed to the 
public -- the 6,600-acre southern portion of the Irvine Co. Open Space Reserve 
-- will be opened next month. 
</P>
<P>
 Donald Bren, chairman of the Irvine Co., said the open space, which is being 
created in exchange for development rights on adjacent land, will rival the 
greatest urban parks in America. 
</P>
<P>
 "It will be the centerpiece of the county, like Central Park is the 
centerpiece of New York," Bren said. "It will be to Orange County what Griffith 
Park is to Los Angeles; a place bringing relaxation and relief from our busy 
lives." 
</P>
<P>
 "It's an incredible asset that has been blocked by barbed wire for more than a 
century," the chairman said of the parcel, stretching from Coast Highway inland 
through Emerald Canyon to the north and from Laguna Canyon Road to Crystal Cove 
State Park. "We think it is socially and botanically important to the 
community." 
</P>
<P>
 Actually, the Irvine Co., the county's largest developer, announced in 1990 
that it intended to eventually make the property accessible to the public via 
docent-led tours. However, the opening of the reserve's southern Emerald Canyon 
portion, which was originally scheduled for last October, had to be postponed 
because of the Laguna Beach fire, which destroyed about 80% of it. 
</P>
<P>
 But in the seven months since then, the area has experienced a dramatic 
recovery, experts say. So starting June 4, it was announced Thursday, 
interested members of the public will for the first time be able to hike 
through the area, accompanied by docents. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want people to witness firsthand the recovery from the fire," said Trish 
Smith, a Nature Conservancy biologist overseeing the project. "It really is 
quite remarkable." 
</P>
<P>
 In 1992, the company signed an agreement with the Nature Conservancy -- a 
nonprofit conservation organization -- to preserve and protect the natural 
resources of the land while developing a program to provide public access to 
it. 
</P>
<P>
 The agreement covered three pieces of Irvine Co. land totaling 11,000 acres. 
The pieces aren't contiguous, but all are along Laguna Canyon Road. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, the program began with the opening of Limestone Canyon to 
docent-led tours. The program is expected to be completed this fall with the 
opening of 2,800 acres in Weir/Gypsum Canyon farther north. 
</P>
<P>
 For now, however, the southern 6,600 acres in Emerald Canyon are getting the 
attention, especially after the land's impressive recovery from the devastating 
fire. 
</P>
<P>
 Indeed, an advance tour by van of the reserve Thursday revealed the bustling 
of natural life resuming. Where six months ago the landscape looked black and 
barren, it now provides nourishment for fields of purple wild hyacinths, red 
Indian paintbrushes and yellow California sunflowers. And a land not too long 
ago seemingly devoid of life now supports red-tailed hawks, meadowlarks, 
bobcats and mule deer. 
</P>
<P>
 According to Smith, strenuous five-hour hiking tours led by Nature Conservancy 
volunteers will be available on the first and third Saturday mornings and 
afternoons of each month beginning June 4. In addition, she said, 13-mile 
mountain cycling tours and 10-mile equestrian tours will be offered twice 
monthly. 
</P>
<P>
 To make reservations for tours, Smith said, interested individuals should call 
(714) 832-7478. 
</P>
<P>
 Some of what the hikers will see was evident during the caravan tour attended 
by officials of both the Irvine Co. and the Nature Conservancy, as well a 
handful of journalists. 
</P>
<P>
 "You can be here and think that you're the only person in the world," said 
Monica Floria, one of the company's senior vice presidents, gazing wistfully at 
the green and brown hills rolling gently into the distance. 
</P>
<P>
 A later stop at a trickling waterfall tumbling some 15 feet down the face of a 
rock by the side of the road elicited some excited responses. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a great experience coming out here," Smith said. "People are always 
amazed at the vastness of the open space." 
</P>
<P>
 She paused before continuing. 
</P>
<P>
 "Every time I come here I experience something totally different," the 
biologist mused. "That's what keeps me excited; there's a surprise around every 
corner." 
</P>
</TEXT>
