<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Michael Arkush 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 CSUN SHINES: The Cal State Northridge Matadors softball team is one-for-one in 
the College World Series in Oklahoma City (C1). Pitcher Amy Windmiller led the 
team in its first-round victory over Missouri by striking out 11 and allowing 
only four hits. Final score: 5-3. 
</P>
<P>
 BUCKING THE EEOC: Rep. Howard P. (Buck) McKeon (R-Santa Clarita) opposes 
proposed Equal Employment Opportunity Commission guidelines intended to help 
curb religious harassment in workplaces (B5). . . . McKeon, a Mormon, claims 
that the proposal would bring about "religion-free zones," but Rep. Howard L. 
Berman (D-Panorama City) counters that it is aimed at "disparaging comments" 
that might make workers "feel that they are not held in good standing." 
</P>
<P>
 BIG HIT: CityWalk (above) is a year old, and no matter how people feel about 
its symbolism and aesthetic value, one thing's for sure: It's a tremendous 
success. In fact, an estimated 2 million people have come specifically to see 
the Universal City complex, twice the number that MCA had hoped for. . . . 
"It's a good place to hang out and not spend too much money," one visitor said. 
See Valley Life! Page 10. 
</P>
<P>
 HOMEWARD BOUND: He may have won a Nobel Prize, but some Russians don't think 
that Alexander Solzhenitsyn is making the smartest decision by moving back to 
his homeland this week. Ellen Moiseyev, hostess at the Moscow Nights restaurant 
in Studio City, says the country has changed dramatically since he went into 
exile two decades ago. . . . "The people who loved him then have left," she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 ABORTION: The two sides of the abortion debate, as expected, had far different 
reactions to President Clinton's signing Thursday of a bill making it a crime 
to deny women access to clinics (A1, A20). . . . Tammy Trouillon, who works at 
a Sherman Oaks clinic, says women now "have the law on their side," while Laura 
Sharp, a Valley spokeswoman for Operation Rescue, said it "turns good, decent 
human beings into felons." Michael Arkush 
</P>
